\begin{abstract}
For $f(k):=k/2^k$ with $k\in\Z_{\ge1}$, we study three questions about representing numbers as sums of \emph{distinct} terms $f(a_k)$ with mutually distinct integers $a_k\ge1$. We prove unconditionally that infinitely many $n$ satisfy $n/2^n=\sum_{k\le t}f(a_k)$ with $t\ge2$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:infmany}), give an exact graph-theoretic reformulation of the all-$n$ question (Proposition~\ref{prop:graph}), verify it for every $n\le2000$ and for an explicit infinite family (Section~\ref{sec:q2}), and leave the general all-$n$ statement as a precise conjecture equivalent to reachability in a corridor digraph. For continuum-many infinite representations, we prove that $x=2$ has $2^{\aleph_0}$ solutions when ``solution'' means an injective sequence $(a_k)$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:seq}), and we construct an explicit irrational $x^{\ast}$ with $2^{\aleph_0}$ distinct set-solutions (Theorem~\ref{thm:sets}). The rational-set case is shown to be exactly as hard as the all-$n$ finite problem. An appendix documents exact-arithmetic verification code.
\end{abstract}

