\section{Statement of the problem and summary of results}\label{sec:summary}

Throughout, write
\[
f(k):=\frac{k}{2^k},\qquad k\in\Z_{\ge1}.
\]
The three questions are:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\arabic*),itemsep=4pt]
\item Are there infinitely many $n$ such that, for some $t\ge2$ and \emph{mutually distinct} integers $a_1,\ldots,a_t\ge1$,
\[
\frac{n}{2^n}=\sum_{k=1}^{t}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}\,?
\]
\item Is the same property true for \emph{every} $n$?
\item Is there a rational $x$ such that
\[
x=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{a_k}{2^{a_k}}
\]
has at least $2^{\aleph_0}$ solutions (with the $a_k$ mutually distinct)?
\end{enumerate}
The requirement that the $a_k$ be mutually distinct is essential: without it the problem is trivial (e.g.\ repeated $f(2)$).

